b'These organizations (along with so many others it would be impossible to list them all) are offering up their skills, resources, and capital for the greater good.'
b'And @Twitter and @Square CEO @Jack is personally donating $1 billion of his Square shares in support of the fight against COVID-19.'
b'@Uber announced it will provide 10 million free rides and food deliveries for frontline health care workers, seniors, and people in need.'
b'@Walmart, together with the Walmart Foundation, is offering support to local communities, which includes donations to food banks and school meal programs.'
b'@SlackHQ has offered non-profit organizations three months of its paid plans for free, helping them adapt to the new norm of collaborating remotely.'
b'The @IBM Summit supercomputer is being used by researchers at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory to study 77 compounds that might stop the coronavirus from infecting host cells.'
b'@abinbev, the maker of @Budweiser, is now manufacturing more than one million bottles of hand sanitizer and donating them to hospitals and frontline workers worldwide.'
b'@3M, which since the COVID-19 outbreak has doubled production of N95 respirators to more than one billion per year, announced it plans to nearly double that number again to two billion.'
b'@GM and @Ford announced they will begin building ventilators, which are in short supply as the number of patients with severe symptoms continues to grow.'
b'@AbbottNews has received emergency use authorization from the FDA for a test that the company says could provide positive COVID-19 results in as little as five minutes.'
b'@Novartis has pledged to donate nearly 130 million doses of generic hydroxychloroquine, which is currently in clinical trials as a potential treatment for COVID-19.'

b'@JNJNews announced the selection of \xe2\x80\x9ca lead vaccine candidate\xe2\x80\x9d and expects to initiate human clinical studies by September. They are also ramping up manufacturing capacity to be able to supply one billion doses of an eventual vaccine.'
b'These efforts are truly remarkable, and I would like to take a moment to highlight just a small fraction of them.'

b'Companies have pivoted to making vaccines, developing therapies, and manufacturing protective equipment and ventilators. \n\nOthers are supporting individuals, families, and communities, including millions who are now unemployed as large segments of the economy have been shut down.'

b'We look forward to the day when we re-open the Floor and welcome back to 11 Wall Street all of the Trading Floor community, who are so important to the markets we operate. \n\nUntil then, our bell continues to ring and our markets remain open for business.'

b'Stocks on the NYSE trade better than on electronic exchanges because of the presence of our DMMs and Floor Brokers. \n\nHuman judgment combined with the latest technology results in reduced volatility and tighter spreads.'

b'The NYSE can also conduct IPOs and bring other new issues to market, even with our Trading Floor closed.\nDespite all this, it\xe2\x80\x99s important to remember that this is a temporary step taken under extraordinary circumstances.'

b'While their unique access and order types are unavailable during the Trading Floor closure, many NYSE Floor Brokers are also connecting remotely and using general electronic order types, the same way orders are entered by member firms not physically present on the Floor.'

b'For example, our Designated Market Makers (DMMs), who provide liquidity for NYSE-listed stocks, continue to do so remotely, with the ability to facilitate opening and closing auctions from a distance.'
b'Under all-electronic NYSE trading, many of the same individuals who make our markets unique continue to play critical roles. They are simply connecting remotely.'
b'The ability to trade in a fully electronic manner is something we test regularly as part of our business continuity planning. We activated these systems with our Opening Bell this morning.'
b'Two, it is our firm belief that the U.S. equity markets must remain open and trading, despite the extreme volatility triggered by this crisis.'

b'We have taken this step for two key reasons. \n\nOne, the safety of our employees and Floor personnel is paramount and, despite their continued willingness keep the Floor operating, we felt it prudent to move to all-electronic trading at this time.'

b'The NYSE took the unprecedented step today of initiating fully electronic trading, closing our Trading Floors temporarily as our nation fights the spread of COVID-19\n\nThis is the first time in the NYSE\xe2\x80\x99s 228-year history that our Floors have been closed while the markets are open'

b'While we are taking the precautionary step of closing the trading floors, we continue to firmly believe the markets should remain open and accessible to investors. \n\nAll NYSE markets will continue to operate under normal trading hours despite the closure of the trading floors.'

b'Closing the markets would not change the underlying causes of the market decline, would remove transparency into investor sentiment, and reduce investors\xe2\x80\x99 access to their money. This would only further compound the current market anxiety. (3/3)'

b'While we are deeply conscious of, and sympathetic to, investors\xe2\x80\x99 concerns around price declines, the market is a reflection of the larger uncertainties that everyone is experiencing during these challenging days. (2/3)'
b'It is important for the markets to remain open, and for them to function in a fair and orderly manner, as they have been. (1/3)'

b'NYSE has taken a number of steps to protect the health and safety of the NYSE community and, importantly, keep the NYSE equity and options trading floors open for business in the days and weeks ahead\n\nRead more: https://t.co/boo0wXI0RX'
b'Here is what I wrote earlier this week about how market-wide circuit breakers function, and why they exist. https://t.co/6LIbT0mOoy'

b'For the second time this week the market-wide circuit breakers halted US equities trading for 15 minutes, functioning exactly as designed.\n\nThis trading pause allows investors to absorb information, better understand what\xe2\x80\x99s happening in the market, and make decisions accordingly.'

b'The halt in trading this morning means that the market-wide circuit breakers functioned exactly as designed. \n\nThese precautionary systems have a long history, and we continue to update them as markets evolve. Our goal is market resiliency during times of stress.'
b'Market-wide circuit breakers enforce a trading pause so that investors have time to absorb information, better understand what\xe2\x80\x99s happening in the market, and make decisions accordingly.'

b'Here\xe2\x80\x99s how they function:\n\nIf the S&P 500 falls 7% from the prior day\xe2\x80\x99s close, it triggers a 15 min trading halt (that\xe2\x80\x99s what happened today). If it falls 13% before 3:25pm, trading halts again for 15 min. And if it falls 20%, then all trading remains halted the rest of the day.'

b'Shortly after today\xe2\x80\x99s market open, the market-wide circuit breakers halted trading for 15 minutes. \n\nI would like to provide some color on how market-wide circuit breakers work, and why they exist.'

b'How do we move forward to address these issues? First, founders and early investors should consider that when companies are open to public investment, society as a whole benefits.\n\nhttps://t.co/TqS5t2t0WB'

b'Another consequence of companies staying private is the potential bad habits that can develop in the absence of the discipline and transparency that public markets require.\n\nhttps://t.co/TqS5t2t0WB'

b'Companies staying private longer contributes to our nation\xe2\x80\x99s wealth-divide. It restricts investment during a company\xe2\x80\x99s best growth years to wealthy individuals and institutions.\n\nhttps://t.co/TqS5t2t0WB'

b'My top priority is advocating on behalf of our listed companies and investors to ensure that the U.S. remains the world\xe2\x80\x99s best equities market place. I will be spending the week further discussing these important issues with both policy makers and the media.'

b'While we are aligned with investors on supporting changes to the U.S. equity pricing landscape, the Pilot does not meet the stated objectives. Instead it is an overly complex government price control experiment imposed on exchanges at the expense of our listed issuers.'

b'Specifically, the SEC\xe2\x80\x99s proposed Transaction Fee Pilot, which bills itself as an analysis of broker routing behavior - but in reality it doesn\xe2\x80\x99t eliminate or even measure conflicts, and ignores 40% of the market.'
